This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with dense semantic correspondence, which is a fundamental problem in computer vision. The use of fully convolutional networks and deep neural networks also suggests that it could belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The mention of object candidate priors and weakly-supervised learning suggests that it could also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. Finally, the use of joint learning and multi-scale sampling suggests that it could belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
